findings.suggestion:
Add integration tests that: (1) Register an MCP server with an invalid command (e.g., 'nonexistent-binary') and verify initialize() returns it in mcpFailed with a meaningful error string. (2) Create a test model whose doGenerate throws an error, call orchestrator.generate(), and verify the error propagates correctly. (3) Call getTools() before initialize() and verify graceful behavior. Example:

it('reports MCP server connection failures in initResult', async () => {
  orchestrator.mcpHub.addServer({ name: 'bad-server', transport: 'stdio', command: 'nonexistent-binary', args: [] });
  const result = await orchestrator.initialize();
  expect(result.mcpFailed.length).toBeGreaterThanOrEqual(1);
  expect(result.mcpFailed[0].error).toBeTruthy();
});

Add boundary condition tests:

it('buildSystemPrompt returns empty string when no base prompt and no skills loaded', () => {
  const orch = createAiOrchestrator({ mcpDbPath: dbPath, builtinSkillsDir: '/nonexistent', userSkillsDir: '/nonexistent' });
  const prompt = orch.buildSystemPrompt();
  expect(prompt).toBe('');
});

it('buildSystemPrompt handles nonexistent skill IDs gracefully', async () => {
  await orchestrator.initialize();
  // Should not throw
  const prompt = orchestrator.buildSystemPrompt(['nonexistent-skill-id']);
  expect(typeof prompt).toBe('string');
});

Add boundary tests for generate():

it('generate with maxSteps=1 limits to single step', async () => {
  const result = await orchestrator.generate(model, [{ role: 'user', content: 'test' }], { maxSteps: 1 });
  expect(result.finishReason).toBeDefined();
});

it('generate with empty messages array does not throw', async () => {
  const result = await orchestrator.generate(model, []);
  expect(result).toBeDefined();
});
